ot</a>. They integrate agent-like AIs that can not only auto-complete but plan and implement code changes across multiple files based on simple, natural language instructions. This shift led many developers to adopt Cursor or Windsurf as their primary IDEs. In response, Microsoft released <a href=\"https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/chat/chat-agent-mode\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Copilot agent mode</a> on April 3rd, 2025. At that point, I hadn’t spent much time with “vibe coding” tools myself, so I decided to dive in and compare Copilot's agent mode with Cursor by building a Twitter clone from scratch using both tools.</p>\n<h2 id=\"copilot\"><a href=\"#copilot\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>Copilot</h2>\n<p>I started with Copilot by providing a fairly detailed initial prompt, to create a Twitter clone using Django, docker compose and Postgres, with the ability to follow other users by username, post/like/reshare tweets and a tweet feed. It started doing it's thing, generating the Django boilerplate code asking for confirmations along the way (you can set to auto-confirm if you want). It produced some sensible database models, but the views were function-based, so I asked to convert them to class-based, something I prefer and could set as a generic rule for future prompts.</p>\n<p>The problem then came when trying to run the project... lots of configuration issues. Some issues were easy to fix with pre-existing knowledge of Django, other were not as obvious. Feeding the error messages into the chat went round in circles. After some frustration I decided it was actually going to be quicker to start a Django project from scratch using <a href=\"https://github.com/cookiecutter/cookiecutter-django\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">django-cookiecutter</a> which got a running project with Django + Postgres + Docker Compose very quickly. A case where reaching for a deterministic tool was the better option.</p>\n<p>Starting from a functional base, I asked Copilot again to generate the Twitter clone. Along the way I had to nudge it in a sensible direction. But then, when trying to run the project, I hit a runtime error. The feeling was very strange, my brain had entered a sort of idle/lazy mode whilst I was waiting for the output, the complete opposite of flow state, I didn't have a gut instinct for what was causing the error message because I hadn't written the code by hand. There was also a strange inertia to putting effort into figuring it out. The path of least resistance was to paste the error message in again, but the attempted solution didn't really solve the issue and effectively hid it by adding a try/except block. After a few more tweaks though... boom! The app was working!</p>\n<p><img class=\"g-image g-image--lazy g-image--loading\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg fill='none' viewBox='0 0 2560 1461' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' xmlns:xlink='http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink'%3e%3cdefs%3e%3cfilter id='__svg-blur-14b7f2d9a050ebf6bd1cc13461d40bf0'%3e%3cfeGaussianBlur in='SourceGraphic' stdDeviation='40'/%3e%3c/filter%3e%3c/defs%3e%3cimage x='0' y='0' filter='url(%23__svg-blur-14b7f2d9a050ebf6bd1cc13461d40bf0)' width='2560' height='1461' xlink:href='data:image/png%3bbase64%2ciVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAEAAAAAlCAYAAADyUO83AAAACXBIWXMAABYlAAAWJQFJUiTwAAAGsklEQVR42tVZS3MbRRD2D4E/kAt/gltu3CgunODOhcAJCu4c4UABxSmhOFPcqFCVxPJTduzIsixbL%2bux0kpaPfY9%2b9E9uyOt1yspUjYpMVWfZ%2bWdnen5prune2anVCqjfF3BVfka9cYttG4PzVYbHa1LdQetdgftjoZms43bZit8pvf8u6P1oOsD9Gbor8AgI2TRdx96f4CdfP4EZ%2bevUCxeonRVxmRqykkPjZFs0B8MYYzG6PZ0aETKYGhIEjqE0XgM1/PhuJ4EP4sA8OmP5wtZK/Bv1W5TuF5Yx/sWwYq%2bveV97iBRhBCydhwHfSJA7/dhEBmMERHB/w/hwrZtmJYF07Tg0UCT6ZS0QiOt6BNx4bc9Io4xJOIsK2q/CWgMi8bjcQa0KLpcwb7U1KFhyHfx9lb0jU2y%2bjQn30/HDk84YBCTDDCoTGkyx/k8dnM5XFwUkT85kVrCHfM7BdM0MZlMIHyfCOvjxW4OR8d5vCoU8Oz5C%2bwfHFAfeygULiRx8psNoMYKAoEymevh0TEKFxd4/mIXN5XKrO8keJGWlR018RkAWbuuG6kYpIoxUQxe%2bbk